    "description": "Using passive voice with modal verbs for formal notes and academic warnings.",
    "display_order": 23,
    "prerequisites": ["time-matrix-22"],
    "lesson_content_markdown": "# The Advanced Passive 2: Modal Passives\n\nIn academic writing, we use **Modals** (must, can, should, must not) with the passive voice to give instructions, warnings, or discuss possibilities.\n\n### 1. How to Make It\nUse the **Modal** + **be** + **Past Participle** (V3).\n\n- **Formula**: Modal + be + V3\n- **Example (Instructions)**: It **should be noted** that the data was collected manually.\n- **Example (Warnings)**: The lab equipment **must not be touched**.\n- **Example (Possibility)**: These results **can be found** on the university website.\n\n### 2. Common Modals in Passive\n- **Must be**: Action is very important/required. (*\"The door must be locked.\"*)\n- **Should be**: Action is recommended. (*\"The sample should be cooled.\"*)\n- **Can be**: Action is possible. (*\"This book can be borrowed.\"*)\n- **Must not be**: Action is forbidden. (*\"Safety rules must not be ignored.\"*)\n\n### 3. Subject-Verb Focus\nNotice that the object (data, equipment, results) starts the sentence. This sounds more objective and formal than saying \"You must not touch the equipment.\"\n\n---",
